\f0\i0\fs32 \cf0 At once the lost boys\'97but where are they? They are no longer there. Rabbits could not have disappeared more quickly.\
I will tell you where they are. With the exception of Nibs, who has darted away to reconnoitre [look around], they are already in their home under the ground, a very delightful residence of which we shall see a good deal presently. But how have they reached it? for there is no entrance to be seen, not so much as a large stone, which if rolled away, would disclose the mouth of a cave. Look closely, however, and you may note that there are here seven large trees, each with a hole in its hollow trunk as large as a boy. These are the seven entrances to the home under the ground, for which Hook has been searching in vain these many moons. Will he find it tonight?\
As the pirates advanced, the quick eye of Starkey sighted Nibs disappearing through the wood, and at once his pistol flashed out. But an iron claw gripped his shoulder.\
\'93Captain, let go!\'94 he cried, writhing.\
Now for the first time we hear the voice of Hook. It was a black voice. \'93Put back that pistol first,\'94 it said threateningly.\
\'93It was one of those boys you hate. I could have shot him dead.\'94\
\'93Ay, and the sound would have brought Tiger Lily\'92s redskins upon us. Do you want to lose your scalp?\'94\
\'93Shall I after him, Captain,\'94 asked pathetic Smee, \'93and tickle him with Johnny Corkscrew?\'94 Smee had pleasant names for everything, and his cutlass was Johnny Corkscrew, because he wiggled it in the wound. One could mention many lovable traits in Smee. For instance, after killing, it was his spectacles he wiped instead of his weapon.\
\'93Johnny\'92s a silent fellow,\'94 he reminded Hook.\
\'93Not now, Smee,\'94 Hook said darkly. \'93He is only one, and I want to mischief all the seven. Scatter and look for them.\'94\
The pirates disappeared among the trees, and in a moment their Captain and Smee were alone. Hook heaved a heavy sigh, and I know not why it was, perhaps it was because of the soft beauty of the evening, but there came over him a desire to confide to his faithful bo\'92sun the story of his life. He spoke long and earnestly, but what it was all about Smee, who was rather stupid, did not know in the least.\
Anon [later] he caught the word Peter.\
\'93Most of all,\'94 Hook was saying passionately, \'93I want their captain, Peter Pan. \'91Twas he cut off my arm.\'94 He brandished the hook threateningly. \'93I\'92ve waited long to shake his hand with this. Oh, I\'92ll tear him!\'94\
\'93And yet,\'94 said Smee, \'93I have often heard you say that hook was worth a score of hands, for combing the hair and other homely uses.\'94\
\'93Ay,\'94 the captain answered, \'93if I was a mother I would pray to have my children born with this instead of that,\'94 and he cast a look of pride upon his iron hand and one of scorn upon the other. Then again he frowned.\
\'93Peter flung my arm,\'94 he said, wincing, \'93to a crocodile that happened to be passing by.\'94\
\'93I have often,\'94 said Smee, \'93noticed your strange dread of crocodiles.\'94\
\'93Not of crocodiles,\'94 Hook corrected him, \'93but of that one crocodile.\'94 He lowered his voice. \'93It liked my arm so much, Smee, that it has followed me ever since, from sea to sea and from land to land, licking its lips for the rest of me.\'94\
\'93In a way,\'94 said Smee, \'93it\'92s sort of a compliment.\'94\
