\b0\fs32 \cf0 Foolish Tootles was standing like a conqueror over Wendy\'92s body when the other boys sprang, armed, from their trees.\
\'93You are too late,\'94 he cried proudly, \'93I have shot the Wendy. Peter will be so pleased with me.\'94\
Overhead Tinker Bell shouted \'93Silly ass!\'94 and darted into hiding. The others did not hear her. They had crowded round Wendy, and as they looked a terrible silence fell upon the wood. If Wendy\'92s heart had been beating they would all have heard it.\
Slightly was the first to speak. \'93This is no bird,\'94 he said in a scared voice. \'93I think this must be a lady.\'94\
\'93A lady?\'94 said Tootles, and fell a-trembling.\
\'93And we have killed her,\'94 Nibs said hoarsely.\
They all whipped off their caps.\
\'93Now I see,\'94 Curly said: \'93Peter was bringing her to us.\'94 He threw himself sorrowfully on the ground.\
\'93A lady to take care of us at last,\'94 said one of the twins, \'93and you have killed her!\'94\
They were sorry for him, but sorrier for themselves, and when he took a step nearer them they turned from him.\
Tootles\'92 face was very white, but there was a dignity about him now that had never been there before.\
\'93I did it,\'94 he said, reflecting. \'93When ladies used to come to me in dreams, I said, \'91Pretty mother, pretty mother.\'92 But when at last she really came, I shot her.\'94\
