\b\fs48 \cf0 Chapter 8 THE MERMAIDS\'92 LAGOON\
\pard\pardeftab720\qj\partightenfactor0

\b0\fs32 \cf0 If you shut your eyes and are a lucky one, you may see at times a shapeless pool of lovely pale colours suspended in the darkness; then if you squeeze your eyes tighter, the pool begins to take shape, and the colours become so vivid that with another squeeze they must go on fire. But just before they go on fire you see the lagoon. This is the nearest you ever get to it on the mainland, just one heavenly moment; if there could be two moments you might see the surf and hear the mermaids singing.\
The children often spent long summer days on this lagoon, swimming or floating most of the time, playing the mermaid games in the water, and so forth. You must not think from this that the mermaids were on friendly terms with them: on the contrary, it was among Wendy\'92s lasting regrets that all the time she was on the island she never had a civil word from one of them. When she stole softly to the edge of the lagoon she might see them by the score, especially on Marooners\'92 Rock, where they loved to bask, combing out their hair in a lazy way that quite irritated her; or she might even swim, on tiptoe as it were, to within a yard of them, but then they saw her and dived, probably splashing her with their tails, not by accident, but intentionally.\
They treated all the boys in the same way, except of course Peter, who chatted with them on Marooners\'92 Rock by the hour, and sat on their tails when they got cheeky. He gave Wendy one of their combs.\
The most haunting time at which to see them is at the turn of the moon, when they utter strange wailing cries; but the lagoon is dangerous for mortals then, and until the evening of which we have now to tell, Wendy had never seen the lagoon by moonlight, less from fear, for of course Peter would have accompanied her, than because she had strict rules about every one being in bed by seven. She was often at the lagoon, however, on sunny days after rain, when the mermaids come up in extraordinary numbers to play with their bubbles. The bubbles of many colours made in rainbow water they treat as balls, hitting them gaily from one to another with their tails, and trying to keep them in the rainbow till they burst. The goals are at each end of the rainbow, and the keepers only are allowed to use their hands. Sometimes a dozen of these games will be going on in the lagoon at a time, and it is quite a pretty sight.\
But the moment the children tried to join in they had to play by themselves, for the mermaids immediately disappeared. Nevertheless we have proof that they secretly watched the interlopers, and were not above taking an idea from them; for John introduced a new way of hitting the bubble, with the head instead of the hand, and the mermaids adopted it. This is the one mark that John has left on the Neverland.\
It must also have been rather pretty to see the children resting on a rock for half an hour after their mid-day meal. Wendy insisted on their doing this, and it had to be a real rest even though the meal was make-believe. So they lay there in the sun, and their bodies glistened in it, while she sat beside them and looked important.\
It was one such day, and they were all on Marooners\'92 Rock. The rock was not much larger than their great bed, but of course they all knew how not to take up much room, and they were dozing, or at least lying with their eyes shut, and pinching occasionally when they thought Wendy was not looking. She was very busy, stitching.\
While she stitched a change came to the lagoon. Little shivers ran over it, and the sun went away and shadows stole across the water, turning it cold. Wendy could no longer see to thread her needle, and when she looked up, the lagoon that had always hitherto been such a laughing place seemed formidable and unfriendly.\
It was not, she knew, that night had come, but something as dark as night had come. No, worse than that. It had not come, but it had sent that shiver through the sea to say that it was coming. What was it?\
There crowded upon her all the stories she had been told of Marooners\'92 Rock, so called because evil captains put sailors on it and leave them there to drown. They drown when the tide rises, for then it is submerged.\
Of course she should have roused the children at once; not merely because of the unknown that was stalking toward them, but because it was no longer good for them to sleep on a rock grown chilly. But she was a young mother and she did not know this; she thought you simply must stick to your rule about half an hour after the mid-day meal. So, though fear was upon her, and she longed to hear male voices, she would not waken them. Even when she heard the sound of muffled oars, though her heart was in her mouth, she did not waken them. She stood over them to let them have their sleep out. Was it not brave of Wendy?\
It was well for those boys then that there was one among them who could sniff danger even in his sleep. Peter sprang erect, as wide awake at once as a dog, and with one warning cry he roused the others.\
He stood motionless, one hand to his ear.\
\'93Pirates!\'94 he cried. The others came closer to him. A strange smile was playing about his face, and Wendy saw it and shuddered. While that smile was on his face no one dared address him; all they could do was to stand ready to obey. The order came sharp and incisive.\
\'93Dive!\'94\
There was a gleam of legs, and instantly the lagoon seemed deserted. Marooners\'92 Rock stood alone in the forbidding waters as if it were itself marooned.\
The boat drew nearer. It was the pirate dinghy, with three figures in her, Smee and Starkey, and the third a captive, no other than Tiger Lily. Her hands and ankles were tied, and she knew what was to be her fate. She was to be left on the rock to perish, an end to one of her race more terrible than death by fire or torture, for is it not written in the book of the tribe that there is no path through water to the happy hunting-ground? Yet her face was impassive; she was the daughter of a chief, she must die as a chief\'92s daughter, it is enough.\
They had caught her boarding the pirate ship with a knife in her mouth. No watch was kept on the ship, it being Hook\'92s boast that the wind of his name guarded the ship for a mile around. Now her fate would help to guard it also. One more wail would go the round in that wind by night.\
In the gloom that they brought with them the two pirates did not see the rock till they crashed into it.\
\'93Luff, you lubber,\'94 cried an Irish voice that was Smee\'92s; \'93here\'92s the rock. Now, then, what we have to do is to hoist the redskin on to it and leave her here to drown.\'94\
It was the work of one brutal moment to land the beautiful girl on the rock; she was too proud to offer a vain resistance.\
Quite near the rock, but out of sight, two heads were bobbing up and down, Peter\'92s and Wendy\'92s. Wendy was crying, for it was the first tragedy she had seen. Peter had seen many tragedies, but he had forgotten them all. He was less sorry than Wendy for Tiger Lily: it was two against one that angered him, and he meant to save her. An easy way would have been to wait until the pirates had gone, but he was never one to choose the easy way.\
There was almost nothing he could not do, and he now imitated the voice of Hook.\
\'93Ahoy there, you lubbers!\'94 he called. It was a marvellous imitation.\
\'93The captain!\'94 said the pirates, staring at each other in surprise.\
\'93He must be swimming out to us,\'94 Starkey said, when they had looked for him in vain.\
\'93We are putting the redskin on the rock,\'94 Smee called out.\
\'93Set her free,\'94 came the astonishing answer.\
\'93Free!\'94\
\'93Yes, cut her bonds and let her go.\'94\
\'93But, captain\'97\'94\
\'93At once, d\'92ye hear,\'94 cried Peter, \'93or I\'92ll plunge my hook in you.\'94\
\'93This is queer!\'94 Smee gasped.\
\'93Better do what the captain orders,\'94 said Starkey nervously.\
\'93Ay, ay,\'94 Smee said, and he cut Tiger Lily\'92s cords. At once like an eel she slid between Starkey\'92s legs into the water.\
Of course Wendy was very elated over Peter\'92s cleverness; but she knew that he would be elated also and very likely crow and thus betray himself, so at once her hand went out to cover his mouth. But it was stayed even in the act, for \'93Boat ahoy!\'94 rang over the lagoon in Hook\'92s voice, and this time it was not Peter who had spoken.\
Peter may have been about to crow, but his face puckered in a whistle of surprise instead.\
\'93Boat ahoy!\'94 again came the voice.\
Now Wendy understood. The real Hook was also in the water.\
He was swimming to the boat, and as his men showed a light to guide him he had soon reached them. In the light of the lantern Wendy saw his hook grip the boat\'92s side; she saw his evil swarthy face as he rose dripping from the water, and, quaking, she would have liked to swim away, but Peter would not budge. He was tingling with life and also top-heavy with conceit. \'93Am I not a wonder, oh, I am a wonder!\'94 he whispered to her, and though she thought so also, she was really glad for the sake of his reputation that no one heard him except herself.\
He signed to her to listen.\
The two pirates were very curious to know what had brought their captain to them, but he sat with his head on his hook in a position of profound melancholy.\
\'93Captain, is all well?\'94 they asked timidly, but he answered with a hollow moan.\
\'93He sighs,\'94 said Smee.\
\'93He sighs again,\'94 said Starkey.\
\'93And yet a third time he sighs,\'94 said Smee.\
Then at last he spoke passionately.\
\'93The game\'92s up,\'94 he cried, \'93those boys have found a mother.\'94\
Affrighted though she was, Wendy swelled with pride.\
\'93O evil day!\'94 cried Starkey.\
\'93What\'92s a mother?\'94 asked the ignorant Smee.\
Wendy was so shocked that she exclaimed. \'93He doesn\'92t know!\'94 and always after this she felt that if you could have a pet pirate Smee would be her one.\
Peter pulled her beneath the water, for Hook had started up, crying, \'93What was that?\'94\
\'93I heard nothing,\'94 said Starkey, raising the lantern over the waters, and as the pirates looked they saw a strange sight. It was the nest I have told you of, floating on the lagoon, and the Never bird was sitting on it.\
\'93See,\'94 said Hook in answer to Smee\'92s question, \'93that is a mother. What a lesson! The nest must have fallen into the water, but would the mother desert her eggs? No.\'94\
There was a break in his voice, as if for a moment he recalled innocent days when\'97but he brushed away this weakness with his hook.\
Smee, much impressed, gazed at the bird as the nest was borne past, but the more suspicious Starkey said, \'93If she is a mother, perhaps she is hanging about here to help Peter.\'94\
Hook winced. \'93Ay,\'94 he said, \'93that is the fear that haunts me.\'94\
He was roused from this dejection by Smee\'92s eager voice.\
\'93Captain,\'94 said Smee, \'93could we not kidnap these boys\'92 mother and make her our mother?\'94\
\'93It is a princely scheme,\'94 cried Hook, and at once it took practical shape in his great brain. \'93We will seize the children and carry them to the boat: the boys we will make walk the plank, and Wendy shall be our mother.\'94\
Again Wendy forgot herself.\
\'93Never!\'94 she cried, and bobbed.\
\'93What was that?\'94\
But they could see nothing. They thought it must have been a leaf in the wind. \'93Do you agree, my bullies?\'94 asked Hook.\
\'93There is my hand on it,\'94 they both said.\
\'93And there is my hook. Swear.\'94\
They all swore. By this time they were on the rock, and suddenly Hook remembered Tiger Lily.\
\'93Where is the redskin?\'94 he demanded abruptly.\
He had a playful humour at moments, and they thought this was one of the moments.\
\'93That is all right, captain,\'94 Smee answered complacently; \'93we let her go.\'94\
\'93Let her go!\'94 cried Hook.\
\'93\'91Twas your own orders,\'94 the bo\'92sun faltered.\
\'93You called over the water to us to let her go,\'94 said Starkey.\
\'93Brimstone and gall,\'94 thundered Hook, \'93what cozening [cheating] is going on here!\'94 His face had gone black with rage, but he saw that they believed their words, and he was startled. \'93Lads,\'94 he said, shaking a little, \'93I gave no such order.\'94\
\'93It is passing queer,\'94 Smee said, and they all fidgeted uncomfortably. Hook raised his voice, but there was a quiver in it.\
\'93Spirit that haunts this dark lagoon to-night,\'94 he cried, \'93dost hear me?\'94\
Of course Peter should have kept quiet, but of course he did not. He immediately answered in Hook\'92s voice:\
\'93Odds, bobs, hammer and tongs, I hear you.\'94\
In that supreme moment Hook did not blanch, even at the gills, but Smee and Starkey clung to each other in terror.\
\'93Who are you, stranger? Speak!\'94 Hook demanded.\
\'93I am James Hook,\'94 replied the voice, \'93captain of the JOLLY ROGER.\'94\
\'93You are not; you are not,\'94 Hook cried hoarsely.\
\'93Brimstone and gall,\'94 the voice retorted, \'93say that again, and I\'92ll cast anchor in you.\'94\
Hook tried a more ingratiating manner. \'93If you are Hook,\'94 he said almost humbly, \'93come tell me, who am I?\'94\
\'93A codfish,\'94 replied the voice, \'93only a codfish.\'94\
\'93A codfish!\'94 Hook echoed blankly, and it was then, but not till then, that his proud spirit broke. He saw his men draw back from him.\
\'93Have we been captained all this time by a codfish!\'94 they muttered. \'93It is lowering to our pride.\'94\
They were his dogs snapping at him, but, tragic figure though he had become, he scarcely heeded them. Against such fearful evidence it was not their belief in him that he needed, it was his own. He felt his ego slipping from him. \'93Don\'92t desert me, bully,\'94 he whispered hoarsely to it.\
In his dark nature there was a touch of the feminine, as in all the great pirates, and it sometimes gave him intuitions. Suddenly he tried the guessing game.\
\'93Hook,\'94 he called, \'93have you another voice?\'94\
Now Peter could never resist a game, and he answered blithely in his own voice, \'93I have.\'94\
\'93And another name?\'94\
\'93Ay, ay.\'94\
\'93Vegetable?\'94 asked Hook.\
\'93No.\'94\
\'93Mineral?\'94\
\'93No.\'94\
\'93Animal?\'94\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\'93Man?\'94\
\'93No!\'94 This answer rang out scornfully.\
\'93Boy?\'94\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\'93Ordinary boy?\'94\
\'93No!\'94\
\'93Wonderful boy?\'94\
To Wendy\'92s pain the answer that rang out this time was \'93Yes.\'94\
\'93Are you in England?\'94\
\'93No.\'94\
\'93Are you here?\'94\
\'93Yes.\'94\
Hook was completely puzzled. \'93You ask him some questions,\'94 he said to the others, wiping his damp brow.\
Smee reflected. \'93I can\'92t think of a thing,\'94 he said regretfully.\
\'93Can\'92t guess, can\'92t guess!\'94 crowed Peter. \'93Do you give it up?\'94\
Of course in his pride he was carrying the game too far, and the miscreants [villains] saw their chance.\
\'93Yes, yes,\'94 they answered eagerly.\
\'93Well, then,\'94 he cried, \'93I am Peter Pan.\'94\
Pan!\
In a moment Hook was himself again, and Smee and Starkey were his faithful henchmen.\
\'93Now we have him,\'94 Hook shouted. \'93Into the water, Smee. Starkey, mind the boat. Take him dead or alive!\'94\
He leaped as he spoke, and simultaneously came the gay voice of Peter.\
\'93Are you ready, boys?\'94\
\'93Ay, ay,\'94 from various parts of the lagoon.\
\'93Then lam into the pirates.\'94\
The fight was short and sharp. First to draw blood was John, who gallantly climbed into the boat and held Starkey. There was fierce struggle, in which the cutlass was torn from the pirate\'92s grasp. He wriggled overboard and John leapt after him. The dinghy drifted away.\
Here and there a head bobbed up in the water, and there was a flash of steel followed by a cry or a whoop. In the confusion some struck at their own side. The corkscrew of Smee got Tootles in the fourth rib, but he was himself pinked [nicked] in turn by Curly. Farther from the rock Starkey was pressing Slightly and the twins hard.\
Where all this time was Peter? He was seeking bigger game.\
The others were all brave boys, and they must not be blamed for backing from the pirate captain. His iron claw made a circle of dead water round him, from which they fled like affrighted fishes.\
But there was one who did not fear him: there was one prepared to enter that circle.\
Strangely, it was not in the water that they met. Hook rose to the rock to breathe, and at the same moment Peter scaled it on the opposite side. The rock was slippery as a ball, and they had to crawl rather than climb. Neither knew that the other was coming. Each feeling for a grip met the other\'92s arm: in surprise they raised their heads; their faces were almost touching; so they met.\
Some of the greatest heroes have confessed that just before they fell to [began combat] they had a sinking [feeling in the stomach]. Had it been so with Peter at that moment I would admit it. After all, he was the only man that the Sea-Cook had feared. But Peter had no sinking, he had one feeling only, gladness; and he gnashed his pretty teeth with joy. Quick as thought he snatched a knife from Hook\'92s belt and was about to drive it home, when he saw that he was higher up the rock than his foe. It would not have been fighting fair. He gave the pirate a hand to help him up.\
It was then that Hook bit him.\
Not the pain of this but its unfairness was what dazed Peter. It made him quite helpless. He could only stare, horrified. Every child is affected thus the first time he is treated unfairly. All he thinks he has a right to when he comes to you to be yours is fairness. After you have been unfair to him he will love you again, but will never afterwards be quite the same boy. No one ever gets over the first unfairness; no one except Peter. He often met it, but he always forgot it. I suppose that was the real difference between him and all the rest.\
So when he met it now it was like the first time; and he could just stare, helpless. Twice the iron hand clawed him.\
A few moments afterwards the other boys saw Hook in the water striking wildly for the ship; no elation on the pestilent face now, only white fear, for the crocodile was in dogged pursuit of him. On ordinary occasions the boys would have swum alongside cheering; but now they were uneasy, for they had lost both Peter and Wendy, and were scouring the lagoon for them, calling them by name. They found the dinghy and went home in it, shouting \'93Peter, Wendy\'94 as they went, but no answer came save mocking laughter from the mermaids. \'93They must be swimming back or flying,\'94 the boys concluded. They were not very anxious, because they had such faith in Peter. They chuckled, boylike, because they would be late for bed; and it was all mother Wendy\'92s fault!\
When their voices died away there came cold silence over the lagoon, and then a feeble cry.\
\'93Help, help!\'94\
Two small figures were beating against the rock; the girl had fainted and lay on the boy\'92s arm. With a last effort Peter pulled her up the rock and then lay down beside her. Even as he also fainted he saw that the water was rising. He knew that they would soon be drowned, but he could do no more.\
As they lay side by side a mermaid caught Wendy by the feet, and began pulling her softly into the water. Peter, feeling her slip from him, woke with a start, and was just in time to draw her back. But he had to tell her the truth.\
\'93We are on the rock, Wendy,\'94 he said, \'93but it is growing smaller. Soon the water will be over it.\'94\
She did not understand even now.\
\'93We must go,\'94 she said, almost brightly.\
\'93Yes,\'94 he answered faintly.\
\'93Shall we swim or fly, Peter?\'94\
He had to tell her.\
\'93Do you think you could swim or fly as far as the island, Wendy, without my help?\'94\
She had to admit that she was too tired.\
He moaned.\
\'93What is it?\'94 she asked, anxious about him at once.\
\'93I can\'92t help you, Wendy. Hook wounded me. I can neither fly nor swim.\'94\
\'93Do you mean we shall both be drowned?\'94\
\'93Look how the water is rising.\'94\
They put their hands over their eyes to shut out the sight. They thought they would soon be no more. As they sat thus something brushed against Peter as light as a kiss, and stayed there, as if saying timidly, \'93Can I be of any use?\'94\
It was the tail of a kite, which Michael had made some days before. It had torn itself out of his hand and floated away.\
\'93Michael\'92s kite,\'94 Peter said without interest, but next moment he had seized the tail, and was pulling the kite toward him.\
\'93It lifted Michael off the ground,\'94 he cried; \'93why should it not carry you?\'94\
\'93Both of us!\'94\
\'93It can\'92t lift two; Michael and Curly tried.\'94\
\'93Let us draw lots,\'94 Wendy said bravely.\
\'93And you a lady; never.\'94 Already he had tied the tail round her. She clung to him; she refused to go without him; but with a \'93Good-bye, Wendy,\'94 he pushed her from the rock; and in a few minutes she was borne out of his sight. Peter was alone on the lagoon.\
The rock was very small now; soon it would be submerged. Pale rays of light tiptoed across the waters; and by and by there was to be heard a sound at once the most musical and the most melancholy in the world: the mermaids calling to the moon.\
Peter was not quite like other boys; but he was afraid at last. A tremour ran through him, like a shudder passing over the sea; but on the sea one shudder follows another till there are hundreds of them, and Peter felt just the one. Next moment he was standing erect on the rock again, with that smile on his face and a drum beating within him. It was saying, \'93To die will be an awfully big adventure.\'94\
