\b\fs48 \cf0 Chapter 10 THE HAPPY HOME\
\pard\pardeftab720\qj\partightenfactor0

\b0\fs32 \cf0 One important result of the brush [with the pirates] on the lagoon was that it made the redskins their friends. Peter had saved Tiger Lily from a dreadful fate, and now there was nothing she and her braves would not do for him. All night they sat above, keeping watch over the home under the ground and awaiting the big attack by the pirates which obviously could not be much longer delayed. Even by day they hung about, smoking the pipe of peace, and looking almost as if they wanted tit-bits to eat.\
They called Peter the Great White Father, prostrating themselves [lying down] before him; and he liked this tremendously, so that it was not really good for him.\
\'93The great white father,\'94 he would say to them in a very lordly manner, as they grovelled at his feet, \'93is glad to see the Piccaninny warriors protecting his wigwam from the pirates.\'94\
\'93Me Tiger Lily,\'94 that lovely creature would reply. \'93Peter Pan save me, me his velly nice friend. Me no let pirates hurt him.\'94\
She was far too pretty to cringe in this way, but Peter thought it his due, and he would answer condescendingly, \'93It is good. Peter Pan has spoken.\'94\
Always when he said, \'93Peter Pan has spoken,\'94 it meant that they must now shut up, and they accepted it humbly in that spirit; but they were by no means so respectful to the other boys, whom they looked upon as just ordinary braves. They said \'93How-do?\'94 to them, and things like that; and what annoyed the boys was that Peter seemed to think this all right.\
Secretly Wendy sympathised with them a little, but she was far too loyal a housewife to listen to any complaints against father. \'93Father knows best,\'94 she always said, whatever her private opinion must be. Her private opinion was that the redskins should not call her a squaw.\
We have now reached the evening that was to be known among them as the Night of Nights, because of its adventures and their upshot. The day, as if quietly gathering its forces, had been almost uneventful, and now the redskins in their blankets were at their posts above, while, below, the children were having their evening meal; all except Peter, who had gone out to get the time. The way you got the time on the island was to find the crocodile, and then stay near him till the clock struck.\
The meal happened to be a make-believe tea, and they sat around the board, guzzling in their greed; and really, what with their chatter and recriminations, the noise, as Wendy said, was positively deafening. To be sure, she did not mind noise, but she simply would not have them grabbing things, and then excusing themselves by saying that Tootles had pushed their elbow. There was a fixed rule that they must never hit back at meals, but should refer the matter of dispute to Wendy by raising the right arm politely and saying, \'93I complain of so-and-so;\'94 but what usually happened was that they forgot to do this or did it too much.\
\'93Silence,\'94 cried Wendy when for the twentieth time she had told them that they were not all to speak at once. \'93Is your mug empty, Slightly darling?\'94\
\'93Not quite empty, mummy,\'94 Slightly said, after looking into an imaginary mug.\
\'93He hasn\'92t even begun to drink his milk,\'94 Nibs interposed.\
This was telling, and Slightly seized his chance.\
\'93I complain of Nibs,\'94 he cried promptly.\
John, however, had held up his hand first.\
\'93Well, John?\'94\
\'93May I sit in Peter\'92s chair, as he is not here?\'94\
\'93Sit in father\'92s chair, John!\'94 Wendy was scandalised. \'93Certainly not.\'94\
\'93He is not really our father,\'94 John answered. \'93He didn\'92t even know how a father does till I showed him.\'94\
This was grumbling. \'93We complain of John,\'94 cried the twins.\
Tootles held up his hand. He was so much the humblest of them, indeed he was the only humble one, that Wendy was specially gentle with him.\
\'93I don\'92t suppose,\'94 Tootles said diffidently [bashfully or timidly], \'93that I could be father.\'94\
\'93No, Tootles.\'94\
Once Tootles began, which was not very often, he had a silly way of going on.\
\'93As I can\'92t be father,\'94 he said heavily, \'93I don\'92t suppose, Michael, you would let me be baby?\'94\
\'93No, I won\'92t,\'94 Michael rapped out. He was already in his basket.\
\'93As I can\'92t be baby,\'94 Tootles said, getting heavier and heavier and heavier, \'93do you think I could be a twin?\'94\
\'93No, indeed,\'94 replied the twins; \'93it\'92s awfully difficult to be a twin.\'94\
\'93As I can\'92t be anything important,\'94 said Tootles, \'93would any of you like to see me do a trick?\'94\
\'93No,\'94 they all replied.\
Then at last he stopped. \'93I hadn\'92t really any hope,\'94 he said.\
The hateful telling broke out again.\
\'93Slightly is coughing on the table.\'94\
\'93The twins began with cheese-cakes.\'94\
\'93Curly is taking both butter and honey.\'94\
\'93Nibs is speaking with his mouth full.\'94\
\'93I complain of the twins.\'94\
\'93I complain of Curly.\'94\
\'93I complain of Nibs.\'94\
\'93Oh dear, oh dear,\'94 cried Wendy, \'93I\'92m sure I sometimes think that spinsters are to be envied.\'94\
She told them to clear away, and sat down to her work-basket, a heavy load of stockings and every knee with a hole in it as usual.\
\'93Wendy,\'94 remonstrated [scolded] Michael, \'93I\'92m too big for a cradle.\'94\
\'93I must have somebody in a cradle,\'94 she said almost tartly, \'93and you are the littlest. A cradle is such a nice homely thing to have about a house.\'94\
While she sewed they played around her; such a group of happy faces and dancing limbs lit up by that romantic fire. It had become a very familiar scene, this, in the home under the ground, but we are looking on it for the last time.\
There was a step above, and Wendy, you may be sure, was the first to recognize it.\
\'93Children, I hear your father\'92s step. He likes you to meet him at the door.\'94\
Above, the redskins crouched before Peter.\
\'93Watch well, braves. I have spoken.\'94\
And then, as so often before, the gay children dragged him from his tree. As so often before, but never again.\
He had brought nuts for the boys as well as the correct time for Wendy.\
\'93Peter, you just spoil them, you know,\'94 Wendy simpered [exaggerated a smile].\
\'93Ah, old lady,\'94 said Peter, hanging up his gun.\
\'93It was me told him mothers are called old lady,\'94 Michael whispered to Curly.\
\'93I complain of Michael,\'94 said Curly instantly.\
The first twin came to Peter. \'93Father, we want to dance.\'94\
\'93Dance away, my little man,\'94 said Peter, who was in high good humour.\
\'93But we want you to dance.\'94\
Peter was really the best dancer among them, but he pretended to be scandalised.\
\'93Me! My old bones would rattle!\'94\
\'93And mummy too.\'94\
\'93What,\'94 cried Wendy, \'93the mother of such an armful, dance!\'94\
\'93But on a Saturday night,\'94 Slightly insinuated.\
It was not really Saturday night, at least it may have been, for they had long lost count of the days; but always if they wanted to do anything special they said this was Saturday night, and then they did it.\
\'93Of course it is Saturday night, Peter,\'94 Wendy said, relenting.\
\'93People of our figure, Wendy!\'94\
\'93But it is only among our own progeny [children].\'94\
\'93True, true.\'94\
So they were told they could dance, but they must put on their nighties first.\
\'93Ah, old lady,\'94 Peter said aside to Wendy, warming himself by the fire and looking down at her as she sat turning a heel, \'93there is nothing more pleasant of an evening for you and me when the day\'92s toil is over than to rest by the fire with the little ones near by.\'94\
\'93It is sweet, Peter, isn\'92t it?\'94 Wendy said, frightfully gratified. \'93Peter, I think Curly has your nose.\'94\
\'93Michael takes after you.\'94\
She went to him and put her hand on his shoulder.\
\'93Dear Peter,\'94 she said, \'93with such a large family, of course, I have now passed my best, but you don\'92t want to [ex]change me, do you?\'94\
\'93No, Wendy.\'94\
Certainly he did not want a change, but he looked at her uncomfortably, blinking, you know, like one not sure whether he was awake or asleep.\
\'93Peter, what is it?\'94\
\'93I was just thinking,\'94 he said, a little scared. \'93It is only make-believe, isn\'92t it, that I am their father?\'94\
\'93Oh yes,\'94 Wendy said primly [formally and properly].\
\'93You see,\'94 he continued apologetically, \'93it would make me seem so old to be their real father.\'94\
\'93But they are ours, Peter, yours and mine.\'94\
\'93But not really, Wendy?\'94 he asked anxiously.\
\'93Not if you don\'92t wish it,\'94 she replied; and she distinctly heard his sigh of relief. \'93Peter,\'94 she asked, trying to speak firmly, \'93what are your exact feelings to [about] me?\'94\
\'93Those of a devoted son, Wendy.\'94\
\'93I thought so,\'94 she said, and went and sat by herself at the extreme end of the room.\
\'93You are so queer,\'94 he said, frankly puzzled, \'93and Tiger Lily is just the same. There is something she wants to be to me, but she says it is not my mother.\'94\
\'93No, indeed, it is not,\'94 Wendy replied with frightful emphasis. Now we know why she was prejudiced against the redskins.\
\'93Then what is it?\'94\
\'93It isn\'92t for a lady to tell.\'94\
\'93Oh, very well,\'94 Peter said, a little nettled. \'93Perhaps Tinker Bell will tell me.\'94\
\'93Oh yes, Tinker Bell will tell you,\'94 Wendy retorted scornfully. \'93She is an abandoned little creature.\'94\
Here Tink, who was in her bedroom, eavesdropping, squeaked out something impudent.\
\'93She says she glories in being abandoned,\'94 Peter interpreted.\
He had a sudden idea. \'93Perhaps Tink wants to be my mother?\'94\
\'93You silly ass!\'94 cried Tinker Bell in a passion.\
She had said it so often that Wendy needed no translation.\
\'93I almost agree with her,\'94 Wendy snapped. Fancy Wendy snapping! But she had been much tried, and she little knew what was to happen before the night was out. If she had known she would not have snapped.\
None of them knew. Perhaps it was best not to know. Their ignorance gave them one more glad hour; and as it was to be their last hour on the island, let us rejoice that there were sixty glad minutes in it. They sang and danced in their night-gowns. Such a deliciously creepy song it was, in which they pretended to be frightened at their own shadows, little witting that so soon shadows would close in upon them, from whom they would shrink in real fear. So uproariously gay was the dance, and how they buffeted each other on the bed and out of it! It was a pillow fight rather than a dance, and when it was finished, the pillows insisted on one bout more, like partners who know that they may never meet again. The stories they told, before it was time for Wendy\'92s good-night story! Even Slightly tried to tell a story that night, but the beginning was so fearfully dull that it appalled not only the others but himself, and he said gloomily:\
\'93Yes, it is a dull beginning. I say, let us pretend that it is the end.\'94\
And then at last they all got into bed for Wendy\'92s story, the story they loved best, the story Peter hated. Usually when she began to tell this story he left the room or put his hands over his ears; and possibly if he had done either of those things this time they might all still be on the island. But to-night he remained on his stool; and we shall see what happened.\
