\b\fs48 \cf0 Chapter 11 WENDY\'92S STORY\
\pard\pardeftab720\qj\partightenfactor0

\b0\fs32 \cf0 \'93Listen, then,\'94 said Wendy, settling down to her story, with Michael at her feet and seven boys in the bed. \'93There was once a gentleman\'97\'94\
\'93I had rather he had been a lady,\'94 Curly said.\
\'93I wish he had been a white rat,\'94 said Nibs.\
\'93Quiet,\'94 their mother admonished [cautioned] them. \'93There was a lady also, and\'97\'94\
\'93Oh, mummy,\'94 cried the first twin, \'93you mean that there is a lady also, don\'92t you? She is not dead, is she?\'94\
\'93Oh, no.\'94\
\'93I am awfully glad she isn\'92t dead,\'94 said Tootles. \'93Are you glad, John?\'94\
\'93Of course I am.\'94\
\'93Are you glad, Nibs?\'94\
\'93Rather.\'94\
\'93Are you glad, Twins?\'94\
\'93We are glad.\'94\
\'93Oh dear,\'94 sighed Wendy.\
\'93Little less noise there,\'94 Peter called out, determined that she should have fair play, however beastly a story it might be in his opinion.\
\'93The gentleman\'92s name,\'94 Wendy continued, \'93was Mr. Darling, and her name was Mrs. Darling.\'94\
\'93I knew them,\'94 John said, to annoy the others.\
\'93I think I knew them,\'94 said Michael rather doubtfully.\
\'93They were married, you know,\'94 explained Wendy, \'93and what do you think they had?\'94\
\'93White rats,\'94 cried Nibs, inspired.\
\'93No.\'94\
\'93It\'92s awfully puzzling,\'94 said Tootles, who knew the story by heart.\
\'93Quiet, Tootles. They had three descendants.\'94\
\'93What is descendants?\'94\
\'93Well, you are one, Twin.\'94\
\'93Did you hear that, John? I am a descendant.\'94\
\'93Descendants are only children,\'94 said John.\
\'93Oh dear, oh dear,\'94 sighed Wendy. \'93Now these three children had a faithful nurse called Nana; but Mr. Darling was angry with her and chained her up in the yard, and so all the children flew away.\'94\
\'93It\'92s an awfully good story,\'94 said Nibs.\
\'93They flew away,\'94 Wendy continued, \'93to the Neverland, where the lost children are.\'94\
\'93I just thought they did,\'94 Curly broke in excitedly. \'93I don\'92t know how it is, but I just thought they did!\'94\
\'93O Wendy,\'94 cried Tootles, \'93was one of the lost children called Tootles?\'94\
\'93Yes, he was.\'94\
\'93I am in a story. Hurrah, I am in a story, Nibs.\'94\
\'93Hush. Now I want you to consider the feelings of the unhappy parents with all their children flown away.\'94\
\'93Oo!\'94 they all moaned, though they were not really considering the feelings of the unhappy parents one jot.\
\'93Think of the empty beds!\'94\
\'93Oo!\'94\
\'93It\'92s awfully sad,\'94 the first twin said cheerfully.\
\'93I don\'92t see how it can have a happy ending,\'94 said the second twin. \'93Do you, Nibs?\'94\
\'93I\'92m frightfully anxious.\'94\
\'93If you knew how great is a mother\'92s love,\'94 Wendy told them triumphantly, \'93you would have no fear.\'94 She had now come to the part that Peter hated.\
\'93I do like a mother\'92s love,\'94 said Tootles, hitting Nibs with a pillow. \'93Do you like a mother\'92s love, Nibs?\'94\
\'93I do just,\'94 said Nibs, hitting back.\
\'93You see,\'94 Wendy said complacently, \'93our heroine knew that the mother would always leave the window open for her children to fly back by; so they stayed away for years and had a lovely time.\'94\
\'93Did they ever go back?\'94\
\'93Let us now,\'94 said Wendy, bracing herself up for her finest effort, \'93take a peep into the future;\'94 and they all gave themselves the twist that makes peeps into the future easier. \'93Years have rolled by, and who is this elegant lady of uncertain age alighting at London Station?\'94\
\'93O Wendy, who is she?\'94 cried Nibs, every bit as excited as if he didn\'92t know.\
\'93Can it be\'97yes\'97no\'97it is\'97the fair Wendy!\'94\
\'93Oh!\'94\
\'93And who are the two noble portly figures accompanying her, now grown to man\'92s estate? Can they be John and Michael? They are!\'94\
\'93Oh!\'94\
\'93\'91See, dear brothers,\'92 says Wendy pointing upwards, \'91there is the window still standing open. Ah, now we are rewarded for our sublime faith in a mother\'92s love.\'92 So up they flew to their mummy and daddy, and pen cannot describe the happy scene, over which we draw a veil.\'94\
That was the story, and they were as pleased with it as the fair narrator herself. Everything just as it should be, you see. Off we skip like the most heartless things in the world, which is what children are, but so attractive; and we have an entirely selfish time, and then when we have need of special attention we nobly return for it, confident that we shall be rewarded instead of smacked.\
So great indeed was their faith in a mother\'92s love that they felt they could afford to be callous for a bit longer.\
But there was one there who knew better, and when Wendy finished he uttered a hollow groan.\
\'93What is it, Peter?\'94 she cried, running to him, thinking he was ill. She felt him solicitously, lower down than his chest. \'93Where is it, Peter?\'94\
\'93It isn\'92t that kind of pain,\'94 Peter replied darkly.\
\'93Then what kind is it?\'94\
\'93Wendy, you are wrong about mothers.\'94\
They all gathered round him in affright, so alarming was his agitation; and with a fine candour he told them what he had hitherto concealed.\
\'93Long ago,\'94 he said, \'93I thought like you that my mother would always keep the window open for me, so I stayed away for moons and moons and moons, and then flew back; but the window was barred, for mother had forgotten all about me, and there was another little boy sleeping in my bed.\'94\
I am not sure that this was true, but Peter thought it was true; and it scared them.\
\'93Are you sure mothers are like that?\'94\
\'93Yes.\'94\
So this was the truth about mothers. The toads!\
Still it is best to be careful; and no one knows so quickly as a child when he should give in. \'93Wendy, let us [let\'92s] go home,\'94 cried John and Michael together.\
\'93Yes,\'94 she said, clutching them.\
\'93Not to-night?\'94 asked the lost boys bewildered. They knew in what they called their hearts that one can get on quite well without a mother, and that it is only the mothers who think you can\'92t.\
\'93At once,\'94 Wendy replied resolutely, for the horrible thought had come to her: \'93Perhaps mother is in half mourning by this time.\'94\
This dread made her forgetful of what must be Peter\'92s feelings, and she said to him rather sharply, \'93Peter, will you make the necessary arrangements?\'94\
\'93If you wish it,\'94 he replied, as coolly as if she had asked him to pass the nuts.\
Not so much as a sorry-to-lose-you between them! If she did not mind the parting, he was going to show her, was Peter, that neither did he.\
But of course he cared very much; and he was so full of wrath against grown-ups, who, as usual, were spoiling everything, that as soon as he got inside his tree he breathed intentionally quick short breaths at the rate of about five to a second. He did this because there is a saying in the Neverland that, every time you breathe, a grown-up dies; and Peter was killing them off vindictively as fast as possible.\
Then having given the necessary instructions to the redskins he returned to the home, where an unworthy scene had been enacted in his absence. Panic-stricken at the thought of losing Wendy the lost boys had advanced upon her threateningly.\
\'93It will be worse than before she came,\'94 they cried.\
\'93We shan\'92t let her go.\'94\
\'93Let\'92s keep her prisoner.\'94\
\'93Ay, chain her up.\'94\
In her extremity an instinct told her to which of them to turn.\
\'93Tootles,\'94 she cried, \'93I appeal to you.\'94\
Was it not strange? She appealed to Tootles, quite the silliest one.\
Grandly, however, did Tootles respond. For that one moment he dropped his silliness and spoke with dignity.\
\'93I am just Tootles,\'94 he said, \'93and nobody minds me. But the first who does not behave to Wendy like an English gentleman I will blood him severely.\'94\
He drew back his hanger; and for that instant his sun was at noon. The others held back uneasily. Then Peter returned, and they saw at once that they would get no support from him. He would keep no girl in the Neverland against her will.\
\'93Wendy,\'94 he said, striding up and down, \'93I have asked the redskins to guide you through the wood, as flying tires you so.\'94\
\'93Thank you, Peter.\'94\
\'93Then,\'94 he continued, in the short sharp voice of one accustomed to be obeyed, \'93Tinker Bell will take you across the sea. Wake her, Nibs.\'94\
Nibs had to knock twice before he got an answer, though Tink had really been sitting up in bed listening for some time.\
\'93Who are you? How dare you? Go away,\'94 she cried.\
\'93You are to get up, Tink,\'94 Nibs called, \'93and take Wendy on a journey.\'94\
Of course Tink had been delighted to hear that Wendy was going; but she was jolly well determined not to be her courier, and she said so in still more offensive language. Then she pretended to be asleep again.\
\'93She says she won\'92t!\'94 Nibs exclaimed, aghast at such insubordination, whereupon Peter went sternly toward the young lady\'92s chamber.\
\'93Tink,\'94 he rapped out, \'93if you don\'92t get up and dress at once I will open the curtains, and then we shall all see you in your negligee [nightgown].\'94\
This made her leap to the floor. \'93Who said I wasn\'92t getting up?\'94 she cried.\
In the meantime the boys were gazing very forlornly at Wendy, now equipped with John and Michael for the journey. By this time they were dejected, not merely because they were about to lose her, but also because they felt that she was going off to something nice to which they had not been invited. Novelty was beckoning to them as usual.\
Crediting them with a nobler feeling Wendy melted.\
\'93Dear ones,\'94 she said, \'93if you will all come with me I feel almost sure I can get my father and mother to adopt you.\'94\
The invitation was meant specially for Peter, but each of the boys was thinking exclusively of himself, and at once they jumped with joy.\
\'93But won\'92t they think us rather a handful?\'94 Nibs asked in the middle of his jump.\
\'93Oh no,\'94 said Wendy, rapidly thinking it out, \'93it will only mean having a few beds in the drawing-room; they can be hidden behind the screens on first Thursdays.\'94\
\'93Peter, can we go?\'94 they all cried imploringly. They took it for granted that if they went he would go also, but really they scarcely cared. Thus children are ever ready, when novelty knocks, to desert their dearest ones.\
\'93All right,\'94 Peter replied with a bitter smile, and immediately they rushed to get their things.\
\'93And now, Peter,\'94 Wendy said, thinking she had put everything right, \'93I am going to give you your medicine before you go.\'94 She loved to give them medicine, and undoubtedly gave them too much. Of course it was only water, but it was out of a bottle, and she always shook the bottle and counted the drops, which gave it a certain medicinal quality. On this occasion, however, she did not give Peter his draught [portion], for just as she had prepared it, she saw a look on his face that made her heart sink.\
\'93Get your things, Peter,\'94 she cried, shaking.\
\'93No,\'94 he answered, pretending indifference, \'93I am not going with you, Wendy.\'94\
\'93Yes, Peter.\'94\
\'93No.\'94\
