\f0\i0\fs32 \cf0 What was the last line will never be known, for of a sudden the song was stayed by a dreadful screech from the cabin. It wailed through the ship, and died away. Then was heard a crowing sound which was well understood by the boys, but to the pirates was almost more eerie than the screech.\
\'93What was that?\'94 cried Hook.\
\'93Two,\'94 said Slightly solemnly.\
The Italian Cecco hesitated for a moment and then swung into the cabin. He tottered out, haggard.\
\'93What\'92s the matter with Bill Jukes, you dog?\'94 hissed Hook, towering over him.\
\'93The matter wi\'92 him is he\'92s dead, stabbed,\'94 replied Cecco in a hollow voice.\
\'93Bill Jukes dead!\'94 cried the startled pirates.\
\'93The cabin\'92s as black as a pit,\'94 Cecco said, almost gibbering, \'93but there is something terrible in there: the thing you heard crowing.\'94\
The exultation of the boys, the lowering looks of the pirates, both were seen by Hook.\
\'93Cecco,\'94 he said in his most steely voice, \'93go back and fetch me out that doodle-doo.\'94\
Cecco, bravest of the brave, cowered before his captain, crying \'93No, no\'94; but Hook was purring to his claw.\
\'93Did you say you would go, Cecco?\'94 he said musingly.\
Cecco went, first flinging his arms despairingly. There was no more singing, all listened now; and again came a death-screech and again a crow.\
No one spoke except Slightly. \'93Three,\'94 he said.\
Hook rallied his dogs with a gesture. \'93\'91S\'92death and odds fish,\'94 he thundered, \'93who is to bring me that doodle-doo?\'94\
\'93Wait till Cecco comes out,\'94 growled Starkey, and the others took up the cry.\
\'93I think I heard you volunteer, Starkey,\'94 said Hook, purring again.\
\'93No, by thunder!\'94 Starkey cried.\
\'93My hook thinks you did,\'94 said Hook, crossing to him. \'93I wonder if it would not be advisable, Starkey, to humour the hook?\'94\
\'93I\'92ll swing before I go in there,\'94 replied Starkey doggedly, and again he had the support of the crew.\
\'93Is this mutiny?\'94 asked Hook more pleasantly than ever. \'93Starkey\'92s ringleader!\'94\
\'93Captain, mercy!\'94 Starkey whimpered, all of a tremble now.\
\'93Shake hands, Starkey,\'94 said Hook, proffering his claw.\
Starkey looked round for help, but all deserted him. As he backed up Hook advanced, and now the red spark was in his eye. With a despairing scream the pirate leapt upon Long Tom and precipitated himself into the sea.\
\'93Four,\'94 said Slightly.\
\'93And now,\'94 Hook said courteously, \'93did any other gentlemen say mutiny?\'94 Seizing a lantern and raising his claw with a menacing gesture, \'93I\'92ll bring out that doodle-doo myself,\'94 he said, and sped into the cabin.\
\'93Five.\'94 How Slightly longed to say it. He wetted his lips to be ready, but Hook came staggering out, without his lantern.\
\'93Something blew out the light,\'94 he said a little unsteadily.\
\'93Something!\'94 echoed Mullins.\
\'93What of Cecco?\'94 demanded Noodler.\
\'93He\'92s as dead as Jukes,\'94 said Hook shortly.\
His reluctance to return to the cabin impressed them all unfavourably, and the mutinous sounds again broke forth. All pirates are superstitious, and Cookson cried, \'93They do say the surest sign a ship\'92s accurst is when there\'92s one on board more than can be accounted for.\'94\
\'93I\'92ve heard,\'94 muttered Mullins, \'93he always boards the pirate craft last. Had he a tail, captain?\'94\
\'93They say,\'94 said another, looking viciously at Hook, \'93that when he comes it\'92s in the likeness of the wickedest man aboard.\'94\
\'93Had he a hook, captain?\'94 asked Cookson insolently; and one after another took up the cry, \'93The ship\'92s doomed!\'94 At this the children could not resist raising a cheer. Hook had well-nigh forgotten his prisoners, but as he swung round on them now his face lit up again.\
\'93Lads,\'94 he cried to his crew, \'93now here\'92s a notion. Open the cabin door and drive them in. Let them fight the doodle-doo for their lives. If they kill him, we\'92re so much the better; if he kills them, we\'92re none the worse.\'94\
For the last time his dogs admired Hook, and devotedly they did his bidding. The boys, pretending to struggle, were pushed into the cabin and the door was closed on them.\
\'93Now, listen!\'94 cried Hook, and all listened. But not one dared to face the door. Yes, one, Wendy, who all this time had been bound to the mast. It was for neither a scream nor a crow that she was watching, it was for the reappearance of Peter.\
She had not long to wait. In the cabin he had found the thing for which he had gone in search: the key that would free the children of their manacles, and now they all stole forth, armed with such weapons as they could find. First signing them to hide, Peter cut Wendy\'92s bonds, and then nothing could have been easier than for them all to fly off together; but one thing barred the way, an oath, \'93Hook or me this time.\'94 So when he had freed Wendy, he whispered for her to conceal herself with the others, and himself took her place by the mast, her cloak around him so that he should pass for her. Then he took a great breath and crowed.\
To the pirates it was a voice crying that all the boys lay slain in the cabin; and they were panic-stricken. Hook tried to hearten them; but like the dogs he had made them they showed him their fangs, and he knew that if he took his eyes off them now they would leap at him.\
\'93Lads,\'94 he said, ready to cajole or strike as need be, but never quailing for an instant, \'93I\'92ve thought it out. There\'92s a Jonah aboard.\'94\
\'93Ay,\'94 they snarled, \'93a man wi\'92 a hook.\'94\
\'93No, lads, no, it\'92s the girl. Never was luck on a pirate ship wi\'92 a woman on board. We\'92ll right the ship when she\'92s gone.\'94\
Some of them remembered that this had been a saying of Flint\'92s. \'93It\'92s worth trying,\'94 they said doubtfully.\
\'93Fling the girl overboard,\'94 cried Hook; and they made a rush at the figure in the cloak.\
\'93There\'92s none can save you now, missy,\'94 Mullins hissed jeeringly.\
\'93There\'92s one,\'94 replied the figure.\
\'93Who\'92s that?\'94\
\'93Peter Pan the avenger!\'94 came the terrible answer; and as he spoke Peter flung off his cloak. Then they all knew who \'91twas that had been undoing them in the cabin, and twice Hook essayed to speak and twice he failed. In that frightful moment I think his fierce heart broke.\
At last he cried, \'93Cleave him to the brisket!\'94 but without conviction.\
\'93Down, boys, and at them!\'94 Peter\'92s voice rang out; and in another moment the clash of arms was resounding through the ship. Had the pirates kept together it is certain that they would have won; but the onset came when they were still unstrung, and they ran hither and thither, striking wildly, each thinking himself the last survivor of the crew. Man to man they were the stronger; but they fought on the defensive only, which enabled the boys to hunt in pairs and choose their quarry. Some of the miscreants leapt into the sea; others hid in dark recesses, where they were found by Slightly, who did not fight, but ran about with a lantern which he flashed in their faces, so that they were half blinded and fell as an easy prey to the reeking swords of the other boys. There was little sound to be heard but the clang of weapons, an occasional screech or splash, and Slightly monotonously counting\'97five\'97six\'97seven eight\'97nine\'97ten\'97eleven.\
I think all were gone when a group of savage boys surrounded Hook, who seemed to have a charmed life, as he kept them at bay in that circle of fire. They had done for his dogs, but this man alone seemed to be a match for them all. Again and again they closed upon him, and again and again he hewed a clear space. He had lifted up one boy with his hook, and was using him as a buckler [shield], when another, who had just passed his sword through Mullins, sprang into the fray.\
\'93Put up your swords, boys,\'94 cried the newcomer, \'93this man is mine.\'94\
Thus suddenly Hook found himself face to face with Peter. The others drew back and formed a ring around them.\
For long the two enemies looked at one another, Hook shuddering slightly, and Peter with the strange smile upon his face.\
\'93So, Pan,\'94 said Hook at last, \'93this is all your doing.\'94\
\'93Ay, James Hook,\'94 came the stern answer, \'93it is all my doing.\'94\
\'93Proud and insolent youth,\'94 said Hook, \'93prepare to meet thy doom.\'94\
\'93Dark and sinister man,\'94 Peter answered, \'93have at thee.\'94\
Without more words they fell to, and for a space there was no advantage to either blade. Peter was a superb swordsman, and parried with dazzling rapidity; ever and anon he followed up a feint with a lunge that got past his foe\'92s defence, but his shorter reach stood him in ill stead, and he could not drive the steel home. Hook, scarcely his inferior in brilliancy, but not quite so nimble in wrist play, forced him back by the weight of his onset, hoping suddenly to end all with a favourite thrust, taught him long ago by Barbecue at Rio; but to his astonishment he found this thrust turned aside again and again. Then he sought to close and give the quietus with his iron hook, which all this time had been pawing the air; but Peter doubled under it and, lunging fiercely, pierced him in the ribs. At the sight of his own blood, whose peculiar colour, you remember, was offensive to him, the sword fell from Hook\'92s hand, and he was at Peter\'92s mercy.\
\'93Now!\'94 cried all the boys, but with a magnificent gesture Peter invited his opponent to pick up his sword. Hook did so instantly, but with a tragic feeling that Peter was showing good form.\
Hitherto he had thought it was some fiend fighting him, but darker suspicions assailed him now.\
\'93Pan, who and what art thou?\'94 he cried huskily.\
\'93I\'92m youth, I\'92m joy,\'94 Peter answered at a venture, \'93I\'92m a little bird that has broken out of the egg.\'94\
This, of course, was nonsense; but it was proof to the unhappy Hook that Peter did not know in the least who or what he was, which is the very pinnacle of good form.\
\'93To\'92t again,\'94 he cried despairingly.\
He fought now like a human flail, and every sweep of that terrible sword would have severed in twain any man or boy who obstructed it; but Peter fluttered round him as if the very wind it made blew him out of the danger zone. And again and again he darted in and pricked.\
Hook was fighting now without hope. That passionate breast no longer asked for life; but for one boon it craved: to see Peter show bad form before it was cold forever.\
Abandoning the fight he rushed into the powder magazine and fired it.\
\'93In two minutes,\'94 he cried, \'93the ship will be blown to pieces.\'94\
Now, now, he thought, true form will show.\
But Peter issued from the powder magazine with the shell in his hands, and calmly flung it overboard.\
What sort of form was Hook himself showing? Misguided man though he was, we may be glad, without sympathising with him, that in the end he was true to the traditions of his race. The other boys were flying around him now, flouting, scornful; and he staggered about the deck striking up at them impotently, his mind was no longer with them; it was slouching in the playing fields of long ago, or being sent up [to the headmaster] for good, or watching the wall-game from a famous wall. And his shoes were right, and his waistcoat was right, and his tie was right, and his socks were right.\
James Hook, thou not wholly unheroic figure, farewell.\
For we have come to his last moment.\
Seeing Peter slowly advancing upon him through the air with dagger poised, he sprang upon the bulwarks to cast himself into the sea. He did not know that the crocodile was waiting for him; for we purposely stopped the clock that this knowledge might be spared him: a little mark of respect from us at the end.\
He had one last triumph, which I think we need not grudge him. As he stood on the bulwark looking over his shoulder at Peter gliding through the air, he invited him with a gesture to use his foot. It made Peter kick instead of stab.\
At last Hook had got the boon for which he craved.\
\'93Bad form,\'94 he cried jeeringly, and went content to the crocodile.\
Thus perished James Hook.\
\'93Seventeen,\'94 Slightly sang out; but he was not quite correct in his figures. Fifteen paid the penalty for their crimes that night; but two reached the shore: Starkey to be captured by the redskins, who made him nurse for all their papooses, a melancholy come-down for a pirate; and Smee, who henceforth wandered about the world in his spectacles, making a precarious living by saying he was the only man that Jas. Hook had feared.\
Wendy, of course, had stood by taking no part in the fight, though watching Peter with glistening eyes; but now that all was over she became prominent again. She praised them equally, and shuddered delightfully when Michael showed her the place where he had killed one; and then she took them into Hook\'92s cabin and pointed to his watch which was hanging on a nail. It said \'93half-past one!\'94\
The lateness of the hour was almost the biggest thing of all. She got them to bed in the pirates\'92 bunks pretty quickly, you may be sure; all but Peter, who strutted up and down on the deck, until at last he fell asleep by the side of Long Tom. He had one of his dreams that night, and cried in his sleep for a long time, and Wendy held him tightly.\
