\b0\fs32 \cf0 I hope you want to know what became of the other boys. They were waiting below to give Wendy time to explain about them; and when they had counted five hundred they went up. They went up by the stair, because they thought this would make a better impression. They stood in a row in front of Mrs. Darling, with their hats off, and wishing they were not wearing their pirate clothes. They said nothing, but their eyes asked her to have them. They ought to have looked at Mr. Darling also, but they forgot about him.\
Of course Mrs. Darling said at once that she would have them; but Mr. Darling was curiously depressed, and they saw that he considered six a rather large number.\
\'93I must say,\'94 he said to Wendy, \'93that you don\'92t do things by halves,\'94 a grudging remark which the twins thought was pointed at them.\
The first twin was the proud one, and he asked, flushing, \'93Do you think we should be too much of a handful, sir? Because, if so, we can go away.\'94\
\'93Father!\'94 Wendy cried, shocked; but still the cloud was on him. He knew he was behaving unworthily, but he could not help it.\
\'93We could lie doubled up,\'94 said Nibs.\
\'93I always cut their hair myself,\'94 said Wendy.\
\'93George!\'94 Mrs. Darling exclaimed, pained to see her dear one showing himself in such an unfavourable light.\
Then he burst into tears, and the truth came out. He was as glad to have them as she was, he said, but he thought they should have asked his consent as well as hers, instead of treating him as a cypher [zero] in his own house.\
\'93I don\'92t think he is a cypher,\'94 Tootles cried instantly. \'93Do you think he is a cypher, Curly?\'94\
\'93No, I don\'92t. Do you think he is a cypher, Slightly?\'94\
\'93Rather not. Twin, what do you think?\'94\
It turned out that not one of them thought him a cypher; and he was absurdly gratified, and said he would find space for them all in the drawing-room if they fitted in.\
\'93We\'92ll fit in, sir,\'94 they assured him.\
\'93Then follow the leader,\'94 he cried gaily. \'93Mind you, I am not sure that we have a drawing-room, but we pretend we have, and it\'92s all the same. Hoop la!\'94\
He went off dancing through the house, and they all cried \'93Hoop la!\'94 and danced after him, searching for the drawing-room; and I forget whether they found it, but at any rate they found corners, and they all fitted in.\
As for Peter, he saw Wendy once again before he flew away. He did not exactly come to the window, but he brushed against it in passing so that she could open it if she liked and call to him. That is what she did.\
\'93Hullo, Wendy, good-bye,\'94 he said.\
\'93Oh dear, are you going away?\'94\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\'93You don\'92t feel, Peter,\'94 she said falteringly, \'93that you would like to say anything to my parents about a very sweet subject?\'94\
\'93No.\'94\
\'93About me, Peter?\'94\
\'93No.\'94\
Mrs. Darling came to the window, for at present she was keeping a sharp eye on Wendy. She told Peter that she had adopted all the other boys, and would like to adopt him also.\
\'93Would you send me to school?\'94 he inquired craftily.\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\'93And then to an office?\'94\
\'93I suppose so.\'94\
\'93Soon I would be a man?\'94\
\'93Very soon.\'94\
\'93I don\'92t want to go to school and learn solemn things,\'94 he told her passionately. \'93I don\'92t want to be a man. O Wendy\'92s mother, if I was to wake up and feel there was a beard!\'94\
\'93Peter,\'94 said Wendy the comforter, \'93I should love you in a beard;\'94 and Mrs. Darling stretched out her arms to him, but he repulsed her.\
\'93Keep back, lady, no one is going to catch me and make me a man.\'94\
\'93But where are you going to live?\'94\
\'93With Tink in the house we built for Wendy. The fairies are to put it high up among the tree tops where they sleep at nights.\'94\
\'93How lovely,\'94 cried Wendy so longingly that Mrs. Darling tightened her grip.\
\'93I thought all the fairies were dead,\'94 Mrs. Darling said.\
\'93There are always a lot of young ones,\'94 explained Wendy, who was now quite an authority, \'93because you see when a new baby laughs for the first time a new fairy is born, and as there are always new babies there are always new fairies. They live in nests on the tops of trees; and the mauve ones are boys and the white ones are girls, and the blue ones are just little sillies who are not sure what they are.\'94\
\'93I shall have such fun,\'94 said Peter, with eye on Wendy.\
\'93It will be rather lonely in the evening,\'94 she said, \'93sitting by the fire.\'94\
\'93I shall have Tink.\'94\
\'93Tink can\'92t go a twentieth part of the way round,\'94 she reminded him a little tartly.\
\'93Sneaky tell-tale!\'94 Tink called out from somewhere round the corner.\
\'93It doesn\'92t matter,\'94 Peter said.\
\'93O Peter, you know it matters.\'94\
\'93Well, then, come with me to the little house.\'94\
\'93May I, mummy?\'94\
\'93Certainly not. I have got you home again, and I mean to keep you.\'94\
\'93But he does so need a mother.\'94\
\'93So do you, my love.\'94\
\'93Oh, all right,\'94 Peter said, as if he had asked her from politeness merely; but Mrs. Darling saw his mouth twitch, and she made this handsome offer: to let Wendy go to him for a week every year to do his spring cleaning. Wendy would have preferred a more permanent arrangement; and it seemed to her that spring would be long in coming; but this promise sent Peter away quite gay again. He had no sense of time, and was so full of adventures that all I have told you about him is only a halfpenny-worth of them. I suppose it was because Wendy knew this that her last words to him were these rather plaintive ones:\
\'93You won\'92t forget me, Peter, will you, before spring cleaning time comes?\'94\
Of course Peter promised; and then he flew away. He took Mrs. Darling\'92s kiss with him. The kiss that had been for no one else, Peter took quite easily. Funny. But she seemed satisfied.\
Of course all the boys went to school; and most of them got into Class III, but Slightly was put first into Class IV and then into Class V. Class I is the top class. Before they had attended school a week they saw what goats they had been not to remain on the island; but it was too late now, and soon they settled down to being as ordinary as you or me or Jenkins minor [the younger Jenkins]. It is sad to have to say that the power to fly gradually left them. At first Nana tied their feet to the bed-posts so that they should not fly away in the night; and one of their diversions by day was to pretend to fall off buses [the English double-deckers]; but by and by they ceased to tug at their bonds in bed, and found that they hurt themselves when they let go of the bus. In time they could not even fly after their hats. Want of practice, they called it; but what it really meant was that they no longer believed.\
Michael believed longer than the other boys, though they jeered at him; so he was with Wendy when Peter came for her at the end of the first year. She flew away with Peter in the frock she had woven from leaves and berries in the Neverland, and her one fear was that he might notice how short it had become; but he never noticed, he had so much to say about himself.\
She had looked forward to thrilling talks with him about old times, but new adventures had crowded the old ones from his mind.\
\'93Who is Captain Hook?\'94 he asked with interest when she spoke of the arch enemy.\
\'93Don\'92t you remember,\'94 she asked, amazed, \'93how you killed him and saved all our lives?\'94\
\'93I forget them after I kill them,\'94 he replied carelessly.\
When she expressed a doubtful hope that Tinker Bell would be glad to see her he said, \'93Who is Tinker Bell?\'94\
\'93O Peter,\'94 she said, shocked; but even when she explained he could not remember.\
\'93There are such a lot of them,\'94 he said. \'93I expect she is no more.\'94\
I expect he was right, for fairies don\'92t live long, but they are so little that a short time seems a good while to them.\
Wendy was pained too to find that the past year was but as yesterday to Peter; it had seemed such a long year of waiting to her. But he was exactly as fascinating as ever, and they had a lovely spring cleaning in the little house on the tree tops.\
Next year he did not come for her. She waited in a new frock because the old one simply would not meet; but he never came.\
\'93Perhaps he is ill,\'94 Michael said.\
\'93You know he is never ill.\'94\
Michael came close to her and whispered, with a shiver, \'93Perhaps there is no such person, Wendy!\'94 and then Wendy would have cried if Michael had not been crying.\
Peter came next spring cleaning; and the strange thing was that he never knew he had missed a year.\
That was the last time the girl Wendy ever saw him. For a little longer she tried for his sake not to have growing pains; and she felt she was untrue to him when she got a prize for general knowledge. But the years came and went without bringing the careless boy; and when they met again Wendy was a married woman, and Peter was no more to her than a little dust in the box in which she had kept her toys. Wendy was grown up. You need not be sorry for her. She was one of the kind that likes to grow up. In the end she grew up of her own free will a day quicker than other girls.\
All the boys were grown up and done for by this time; so it is scarcely worth while saying anything more about them. You may see the twins and Nibs and Curly any day going to an office, each carrying a little bag and an umbrella. Michael is an engine-driver [train engineer]. Slightly married a lady of title, and so he became a lord. You see that judge in a wig coming out at the iron door? That used to be Tootles. The bearded man who doesn\'92t know any story to tell his children was once John.\
Wendy was married in white with a pink sash. It is strange to think that Peter did not alight in the church and forbid the banns [formal announcement of a marriage].\
Years rolled on again, and Wendy had a daughter. This ought not to be written in ink but in a golden splash.\
She was called Jane, and always had an odd inquiring look, as if from the moment she arrived on the mainland she wanted to ask questions. When she was old enough to ask them they were mostly about Peter Pan. She loved to hear of Peter, and Wendy told her all she could remember in the very nursery from which the famous flight had taken place. It was Jane\'92s nursery now, for her father had bought it at the three per cents [mortgage rate] from Wendy\'92s father, who was no longer fond of stairs. Mrs. Darling was now dead and forgotten.\
There were only two beds in the nursery now, Jane\'92s and her nurse\'92s; and there was no kennel, for Nana also had passed away. She died of old age, and at the end she had been rather difficult to get on with; being very firmly convinced that no one knew how to look after children except herself.\
Once a week Jane\'92s nurse had her evening off; and then it was Wendy\'92s part to put Jane to bed. That was the time for stories. It was Jane\'92s invention to raise the sheet over her mother\'92s head and her own, thus making a tent, and in the awful darkness to whisper:\
\'93What do we see now?\'94\
\'93I don\'92t think I see anything to-night,\'94 says Wendy, with a feeling that if Nana were here she would object to further conversation.\
\'93Yes, you do,\'94 says Jane, \'93you see when you were a little girl.\'94\
\'93That is a long time ago, sweetheart,\'94 says Wendy. \'93Ah me, how time flies!\'94\
\'93Does it fly,\'94 asks the artful child, \'93the way you flew when you were a little girl?\'94\
\'93The way I flew? Do you know, Jane, I sometimes wonder whether I ever did really fly.\'94\
\'93Yes, you did.\'94\
\'93The dear old days when I could fly!\'94\
\'93Why can\'92t you fly now, mother?\'94\
\'93Because I am grown up, dearest. When people grow up they forget the way.\'94\
\'93Why do they forget the way?\'94\
\'93Because they are no longer gay and innocent and heartless. It is only the gay and innocent and heartless who can fly.\'94\
\'93What is gay and innocent and heartless? I do wish I were gay and innocent and heartless.\'94\
Or perhaps Wendy admits she does see something.\
\'93I do believe,\'94 she says, \'93that it is this nursery.\'94\
\'93I do believe it is,\'94 says Jane. \'93Go on.\'94\
They are now embarked on the great adventure of the night when Peter flew in looking for his shadow.\
\'93The foolish fellow,\'94 says Wendy, \'93tried to stick it on with soap, and when he could not he cried, and that woke me, and I sewed it on for him.\'94\
\'93You have missed a bit,\'94 interrupts Jane, who now knows the story better than her mother. \'93When you saw him sitting on the floor crying, what did you say?\'94\
\'93I sat up in bed and I said, \'91Boy, why are you crying?\'92\'94\
\'93Yes, that was it,\'94 says Jane, with a big breath.\
\'93And then he flew us all away to the Neverland and the fairies and the pirates and the redskins and the mermaids\'92 lagoon, and the home under the ground, and the little house.\'94\
\'93Yes! which did you like best of all?\'94\
\'93I think I liked the home under the ground best of all.\'94\
\'93Yes, so do I. What was the last thing Peter ever said to you?\'94\
\'93The last thing he ever said to me was, \'91Just always be waiting for me, and then some night you will hear me crowing.\'92\'94\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\'93But, alas, he forgot all about me,\'94 Wendy said it with a smile. She was as grown up as that.\
\'93What did his crow sound like?\'94 Jane asked one evening.\
\'93It was like this,\'94 Wendy said, trying to imitate Peter\'92s crow.\
\'93No, it wasn\'92t,\'94 Jane said gravely, \'93it was like this;\'94 and she did it ever so much better than her mother.\
Wendy was a little startled. \'93My darling, how can you know?\'94\
\'93I often hear it when I am sleeping,\'94 Jane said.\
\'93Ah yes, many girls hear it when they are sleeping, but I was the only one who heard it awake.\'94\
\'93Lucky you,\'94 said Jane.\
And then one night came the tragedy. It was the spring of the year, and the story had been told for the night, and Jane was now asleep in her bed. Wendy was sitting on the floor, very close to the fire, so as to see to darn, for there was no other light in the nursery; and while she sat darning she heard a crow. Then the window blew open as of old, and Peter dropped in on the floor.\
He was exactly the same as ever, and Wendy saw at once that he still had all his first teeth.\
He was a little boy, and she was grown up. She huddled by the fire not daring to move, helpless and guilty, a big woman.\
\'93Hullo, Wendy,\'94 he said, not noticing any difference, for he was thinking chiefly of himself; and in the dim light her white dress might have been the nightgown in which he had seen her first.\
\'93Hullo, Peter,\'94 she replied faintly, squeezing herself as small as possible. Something inside her was crying \'93Woman, Woman, let go of me.\'94\
\'93Hullo, where is John?\'94 he asked, suddenly missing the third bed.\
\'93John is not here now,\'94 she gasped.\
\'93Is Michael asleep?\'94 he asked, with a careless glance at Jane.\
\'93Yes,\'94 she answered; and now she felt that she was untrue to Jane as well as to Peter.\
\'93That is not Michael,\'94 she said quickly, lest a judgment should fall on her.\
Peter looked. \'93Hullo, is it a new one?\'94\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\'93Boy or girl?\'94\
\'93Girl.\'94\
Now surely he would understand; but not a bit of it.\
\'93Peter,\'94 she said, faltering, \'93are you expecting me to fly away with you?\'94\
\'93Of course; that is why I have come.\'94 He added a little sternly, \'93Have you forgotten that this is spring cleaning time?\'94\
She knew it was useless to say that he had let many spring cleaning times pass.\
\'93I can\'92t come,\'94 she said apologetically, \'93I have forgotten how to fly.\'94\
\'93I\'92ll soon teach you again.\'94\
\'93O Peter, don\'92t waste the fairy dust on me.\'94\
She had risen; and now at last a fear assailed him. \'93What is it?\'94 he cried, shrinking.\
\'93I will turn up the light,\'94 she said, \'93and then you can see for yourself.\'94\
For almost the only time in his life that I know of, Peter was afraid. \'93Don\'92t turn up the light,\'94 he cried.\
She let her hands play in the hair of the tragic boy. She was not a little girl heart-broken about him; she was a grown woman smiling at it all, but they were wet-eyed smiles.\
Then she turned up the light, and Peter saw. He gave a cry of pain; and when the tall beautiful creature stooped to lift him in her arms he drew back sharply.\
\'93What is it?\'94 he cried again.\
She had to tell him.\
\'93I am old, Peter. I am ever so much more than twenty. I grew up long ago.\'94\
\'93You promised not to!\'94\
\'93I couldn\'92t help it. I am a married woman, Peter.\'94\
\'93No, you\'92re not.\'94\
\'93Yes, and the little girl in the bed is my baby.\'94\
\'93No, she\'92s not.\'94\
But he supposed she was; and he took a step towards the sleeping child with his dagger upraised. Of course he did not strike. He sat down on the floor instead and sobbed; and Wendy did not know how to comfort him, though she could have done it so easily once. She was only a woman now, and she ran out of the room to try to think.\
Peter continued to cry, and soon his sobs woke Jane. She sat up in bed, and was interested at once.\
\'93Boy,\'94 she said, \'93why are you crying?\'94\
Peter rose and bowed to her, and she bowed to him from the bed.\
\'93Hullo,\'94 he said.\
\'93Hullo,\'94 said Jane.\
\'93My name is Peter Pan,\'94 he told her.\
\'93Yes, I know.\'94\
\'93I came back for my mother,\'94 he explained, \'93to take her to the Neverland.\'94\
\'93Yes, I know,\'94 Jane said, \'93I have been waiting for you.\'94\
When Wendy returned diffidently she found Peter sitting on the bed-post crowing gloriously, while Jane in her nighty was flying round the room in solemn ecstasy.\
\'93She is my mother,\'94 Peter explained; and Jane descended and stood by his side, with the look in her face that he liked to see on ladies when they gazed at him.\
\'93He does so need a mother,\'94 Jane said.\
\'93Yes, I know,\'94 Wendy admitted rather forlornly; \'93no one knows it so well as I.\'94\
\'93Good-bye,\'94 said Peter to Wendy; and he rose in the air, and the shameless Jane rose with him; it was already her easiest way of moving about.\
Wendy rushed to the window.\
\'93No, no,\'94 she cried.\
\'93It is just for spring cleaning time,\'94 Jane said, \'93he wants me always to do his spring cleaning.\'94\
\'93If only I could go with you,\'94 Wendy sighed.\
\'93You see you can\'92t fly,\'94 said Jane.\
Of course in the end Wendy let them fly away together. Our last glimpse of her shows her at the window, watching them receding into the sky until they were as small as stars.\
As you look at Wendy, you may see her hair becoming white, and her figure little again, for all this happened long ago. Jane is now a common grown-up, with a daughter called Margaret; and every spring cleaning time, except when he forgets, Peter comes for Margaret and takes her to the Neverland, where she tells him stories about himself, to which he listens eagerly. When Margaret grows up she will have a daughter, who is to be Peter\'92s mother in turn; and thus it will go on, so long as children are gay and innocent and heartless.\
